**[Goldman Sachs Challenges the AI Job Apocalypse Narrative](#)**  
Contrary to widespread fears, AI is not driving mass unemployment. Instead, it is generating new roles, with approximately 640,000 jobs created in the United States between 2023 and early 2026.  

The demand surge is driven by infrastructure: data centres, power systems and technical maintenance. While some routine tasks are automated, new high-skill roles are emerging. The net impact mirrors past technological revolutions: initial disruption followed by productivity gains and job creation.  

The real risk lies not in AI itself, but in failing to prepare the workforce for a more complex, high-skill economy. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}  

